  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol is the common name for copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O). The blue color is due to the presence of water molecules (ligands) coordinated to the copper(II) ion.\n\nHere's a breakdown of why the color changes:\n\n*   **Hydrated Copper(II) Sulfate (Blue):** In CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O, the copper(II) ion (Cu\u00b2\u207a) is surrounded by water molecules. These water molecules act as ligands, forming a complex ion. The electronic structure of the Cu\u00b2\u207a ion and the interaction with the ligands cause it to absorb certain wavelengths of light in the visible spectrum, and reflect others, giving it a characteristic blue color. Specifically, the d-orbitals of the Cu\u00b2\u207a ion split in energy levels due to the ligand field, and electrons can transition between these levels by absorbing light of a specific wavelength.\n\n*   **Dehydration on Heating:** When blue vitriol is heated, it undergoes dehydration, meaning it loses its water molecules. The reaction is:\n\n    CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O(s) + Heat \u2192 CuSO\u2084(s) + 5H\u2082O(g)\n\n*   **Anhydrous Copper(II) Sulfate (White):** As the water molecules are removed, the coordination environment around the copper(II) ion changes. In anhydrous copper(II) sulfate (CuSO\u2084), the Cu\u00b2\u207a ion is no longer surrounded by water ligands in the same way. Without the water molecules influencing the electronic structure of the copper ion, it no longer absorbs light in the same way. The d-orbital splitting is different, leading to different light absorption properties. In fact, anhydrous copper(II) sulfate absorbs very little visible light, and instead scatters all wavelengths relatively equally, resulting in a white appearance.\n\nIn summary, the blue color of blue vitriol is due to the interaction of the copper(II) ion with water ligands. Heating removes these water molecules, changing the coordination environment around the copper(II) ion and thus altering its light absorption properties, causing it to turn white. Anhydrous copper(II) sulfate is white because it lacks the water ligands necessary to produce the electronic transitions that give rise to the blue color.\n",
